{"id":"1412.8505","submitter":"Alexei Davydov","authors":"Alexei Davydov","title":"Unphysical diagonal modular invariants","comments":"v.2 a theorem by W. Kantor and V. Ostrik is added. arXiv admin note:\n  substantial text overlap with arXiv:1312.7466","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.QA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A modular invariant for a chiral conformal field theory is physical if there\nis a full conformal field theory with the given chiral halves realising the\nmodular invariant. The easiest modular invariants are the charge conjugation\nand the diagonal modular invariants. While the charge conjugation modular\ninvariant is always physical there are examples of chiral CFTs for which the\ndiagonal modular invariant is not physical. Here we give (in group theoretical\nterms) a necessary and sufficient condition for diagonal modular invariants of\n$G$-orbifolds of holomorphic conformal field theories to be physical.\n  Mathematically a physical modular invariant is an invariant of a Lagrangian\nalgebra in the product of (chiral) modular categories. The chiral modular\ncategory of a $G$-orbifold of a holomorphic conformal field theory is the\nso-called (twisted) Drinfeld centre ${\\cal Z}(G,\\alpha)$ of the finite group\n$G$. We show that the diagonal modular invariant for ${\\cal Z}(G)$ is physical\nif and only if the group $G$ has a {\\em double class inverting} automorphism,\nthat is an automorphism $\\phi:G\\to G$ with the property that for any commuting\n$x,y\\in G$ there is $g\\in G$ such that $\\phi(x) = gx^{-1}g^{-1},\\ \\phi(y) =\ngy^{-1}g^{-1}.$\n  Groups without double class inverting automorphisms are abundant and provide\nexamples of chiral conformal field theories for which the diagonal modular\ninvariant is unphysical.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 29 Dec 2014 23:13:11 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 1 Jan 2015 00:38:26 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-01-05"}
